      "id": 1,
      "text": "In 1883, Trenton was briefly called Joppa before a former Confederate soldier renamed it after his Tennessee hometown, which itself honored Trenton, New Jersey.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        1
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trenton%2C_Florida"
    },
    {
      "id": 2,
      "text": "The railroad reached Trenton in 1906, prompting rapid growth, and the city was officially chartered two years later in 1908.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        10
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 2"
      ],
      "source": "https://www.florida-backroads-travel.com/trenton-florida.html"
    },
    {
      "id": 3,
      "text": "The old Gilchrist County Jail on NW 2nd St stands as a well‑preserved historic landmark in Trenton.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        5
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 2"
      ],
      "source": "https://www.florida-backroads-travel.com/trenton-florida.html"
    },
    {
      "id": 4,
      "text": "Trenton serves as the county seat of Gilchrist County and sits roughly 30 miles west of Gainesville.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
